  "texts": [
    "5.2.1] for reductive representations ρ by the ρ-equivariant harmonic map h c: ( B2, c) → (G/K, g sym) from Theorem 4.2.",
    "Moreover, if c minimises E ρ, then h c is weakly conformal and harmonic [SU82, Theorem 1.2].If Γ ≤ G is a torsion-free, co-compact lattice and ρ(π 1 (B)) ≤ Γ, then a ρ-equivariant map h: B → G/K defines a genuine map ȟ: B → Γ\\G/K between compact manifolds.",
    "It follows from [SY79,SU82] that if ρ is injective, then there is a conformal structure c on B 2 such that E ρ (c) = inf c ′ E ρ (c ′).",
    "Hence, for injective representations ρ that map into torsion-free, co-compact lattices, we can always solve the twisted harmonic-Einstein equation (20b) for some conformal structure c. Note that the existence of surface subgroups of cocompact lattices in semisimple Lie groups is known in several cases, for example, in complex semisimple groups and simple rank one symmetric spaces other than SO(2n, 1); see the survey [Kas22] and references therein.In the twisted setting, Labourie [Lab08, Thm.",
    "1.0.3] proved that E ρ is a proper function on Teichmüller space when ρ is a Hitchin representation."
  ],
